TY  - JOUR
T1  - Vicarious Learning And Inferential Accuracy in Adoption Processes
AU  - Terlaak, Ann
AU  - Gong, Yan
Y1  - 2008/10/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.34421979
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.34421979
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 846
EP  - 868
VL  - 33
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We develop a model of inferential vicarious learning that explicates how firms can learn whether to adopt a practice whose value varies across organizations. We first theorize how firms can infer this variation from samples of adopters, nonadopters, abandoners, and nonabandoners. Surprisingly, incomplete samples may allow more accurate inferences than complete ones. We then propose how firms, equipped with an understanding of the variation, can select referent organizations that differ from those identified in previous research.
AB  - We develop a model of inferential vicarious learning that explicates how firms can learn whether to adopt a practice whose value varies across organizations. We first theorize how firms can infer this variation from samples of adopters, nonadopters, abandoners, and nonabandoners. Surprisingly, incomplete samples may allow more accurate inferences than complete ones. We then propose how firms, equipped with an understanding of the variation, can select referent organizations that differ from those identified in previous research.
